## Finding: No Security Headers / CORS / CSP Implementation During Build

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: OWASP A05 (Security Misconfiguration) requires proper security header configuration. No Phase 3 skill covers: Helmet.js integration in NestJS (X-Frame-Options, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy), CORS configuration (which origins, which methods, credential handling), Content Security Policy (CSP) header design, or cookie security attributes beyond what auth_implementation shows for token storage. These are build-time configurations that must be set correctly from day one, not security audit findings fixed in Phase 4.
### Proposed Resolution: Add Part to auth_implementation or create `security_headers` skill. Scope: NestJS Helmet.js setup, CORS configuration best practices, CSP policy design for SPAs, cookie security attributes, and the interaction between CSP and frontend asset loading.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (security_audit): should verify headers are set, not set them. Phase 5 (ship): deployment must not override security headers. Phase 6 (handoff): security headers must be documented.

================================================================

## Finding: No GDPR/Privacy-by-Design Implementation Patterns

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: GDPR Article 25 mandates privacy by design. No Phase 3 skill addresses: right-to-erasure implementation (cascade delete vs. anonymization), data minimization patterns in API responses, consent tracking implementation, data retention policy enforcement in code (scheduled cleanup jobs), PII encryption at rest (field-level encryption), or GDPR-compliant audit logging. The observability skill covers PII redaction in logs (good), but the build phase must also ensure PII is not stored unnecessarily, is encrypted where required, and can be deleted on request.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `privacy_by_design` in Phase 3. Scope: right-to-erasure implementation strategies (hard delete vs. anonymization for audit integrity), data minimization patterns, field-level PII encryption (application-level, not just DB-level), consent model implementation, retention policy scheduling.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (security_audit): privacy review should verify Phase 3 implementation. Phase 5 (legal_compliance): GDPR compliance requires Phase 3 foundations. Phase 6 (handoff): must document what data is stored where and how to delete it.

================================================================

## Finding: No Structured Error Budgets / SLO-Aware Development

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: observability covers alerting rules with thresholds. But no skill teaches: Service Level Objectives (SLOs) definition during build, error budget calculations, SLO-aware feature flags (auto-disable risky features when error budget is depleted), or the SRE practice of baking SLO targets into acceptance criteria during Phase 3. Teams that don't define SLOs during build phase have no principled basis for Phase 4 performance_testing targets.
### Proposed Resolution: Add SLO/error budget section to observability skill. Scope: SLO definition (availability, latency, error rate), error budget math, how to use error budgets to decide release vs. hold, and integration with the alerting rules already in observability.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (performance_testing needs SLO targets to define pass/fail). Phase 5.5 (alpha monitoring against SLOs). Phase 7 (SLO-driven maintenance prioritization).

