## Finding: Structural Assessment — Phase 3 Skill Count vs. Coverage Distribution

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Phase 3 has 50 skills, making it the largest phase in the framework. However, coverage distribution is uneven:
- 15 of 50 skills are vertical domain specializations (trading_systems, game_development, firmware_development, dapp_development, iot_platform, smart_contract_dev, swift_*, java_*, cpp_*, django_*, golang_*, springboot_*, liquid_glass_design, multiplayer_systems, clickhouse_io)
- 8 of 50 skills are pure process (sprint_planning, retrospective, stakeholder_communication, code_review, code_review_response, refactoring, code_changelog, bug_troubleshoot)
- 5 of 50 skills are analytical/decision tools (regex_vs_llm, cost_estimation, prompt_engineering, observability, spec_build)
- Only ~22 of 50 skills cover core build patterns (api_design, backend_patterns, frontend_patterns, auth_implementation, error_handling, database_optimization, docker_development, environment_setup, etl_pipeline, ml_pipeline, notification_systems, content_hash_cache, git_workflow, dashboard_development, data_warehouse, extension_development, website_build, ui_polish)

The cross-cutting concerns gap (security headers, feature flags, event-driven, resiliency, backward compatibility, secret management) represents 6-10 missing skills in the "core build patterns" category—a 27-45% gap in the most critical category.

Industry standard (NIST SSDF, OWASP SAMM) would expect these cross-cutting concerns to be first-class build phase skills, not absent.
### Proposed Resolution: The 25 proposed additions (Waves 1-5 above) would bring the cross-cutting concern coverage to an industry-adequate level. Priority order from the dependency graph above.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Cross-cutting concerns affect ALL phases downstream. Gaps here compound—each missing skill creates a debt that manifests as bugs, security issues, or process failures in Phases 4-7.

